mistral.reason: Alan Walsh was the inventor of the theoretical basis of AAS, but he did not work directly for Techtron. He worked at CSIRO and collaborated with Techtron on their AAS projects, but Techtron's key people in terms of its operations and manufacturing include other individuals like Mr Frew, who was involved in building electronics modules for AAS to CSIRO specifications.

gemma2.reason: The text states that John Willis developed applications for AAS.

qwen2.5.reason: Alan Walsh was not associated with Techtron. He invented AAS at CSIRO, while Techtron was a company that later manufactured and developed AAS instruments under license from CSIRO.
